<h2 id="google-business-profile">Google Business Profile Optimization</h2>

<div class="prose max-w-none">
<p>Your Google Business Profile (formerly Google My Business) directly impacts 78% of local search rankings. HVAC companies with fully optimized profiles rank an average of 2.3 positions higher than competitors with basic listings.</p>

<p>Complete every profile section with HVAC-specific information. The business description should include primary keywords naturally while explaining services clearly. Instead of "We provide HVAC services," write "Licensed HVAC contractors specializing in AC repair, furnace installation, and emergency heating service in [city] and surrounding areas since [year]."</p>

<p>Service categories matter significantly for local rankings. Select all relevant categories: "HVAC Contractor" as primary, then add "Air Conditioning Contractor," "Heating Contractor," "Furnace Repair Service," and "Air Duct Cleaning Service." Companies using 4-6 specific categories rank 31% higher than those with only 1-2 broad categories.</p>

<p>Photo optimization directly influences click-through rates. Upload 25-40 high-quality photos showing trucks with company branding, technicians working, before/after equipment shots, and team photos. HVAC companies with 30+ photos get 42% more profile views and 23% more website clicks.</p>

<p>Review response strategy affects both rankings and conversion rates. Respond to every review within 48 hours using personalized messages that include the customer's name and specific service details. Template responses hurt rankings, but authentic replies improve local search visibility.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="on-page-seo-strategy">On-Page SEO Strategy</h2>

<div class="prose max-w-none">
<p>On-page optimization for HVAC websites focuses on service-specific landing pages that match local search intent. Create dedicated pages for each primary service in each service area. A company serving three cities needs separate "AC Repair Phoenix," "AC Repair Scottsdale," and "AC Repair Tempe" pages, not one generic AC repair page.</p>

<p>Title tag optimization drives significant ranking improvements. Use the format: "[Service] in [City] | [Company Name]" for service pages. Keep titles under 60 characters and include the primary keyword early. "Emergency AC Repair in Phoenix | Arctic Cool HVAC" performs better than "Professional Air Conditioning Repair Services."</p>

<p>Header structure should follow a clear hierarchy that supports user navigation and search engine understanding. Use H1 for the main service title, H2 for service details sections (pricing, process, service area), and H3 for subsections like emergency availability or warranty information.</p>

<p>Local schema markup helps Google understand your business context and improves rich snippet appearances. Implement LocalBusiness schema on your homepage and Service schema on individual service pages. Companies using proper schema markup see 15-25% improvements in local search visibility.</p>

<p>Internal linking between service pages and location pages creates topical authority and helps distribute page authority throughout your site. Link from your furnace repair page to your heating maintenance page, and from city-specific pages to relevant service pages using descriptive anchor text.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="content-marketing-approach">Content Marketing for HVAC Companies</h2>

<div class="prose max-w-none">
<p>Content marketing for HVAC companies works best when focused on solving customer problems at different stages of the buying journey. Emergency repair content captures immediate-need customers, while educational maintenance content builds trust with planning-ahead homeowners.</p>

<p>Seasonal content timing aligns with HVAC demand patterns. Publish AC-related content in March-May before peak summer demand, and heating content in September-November before winter. Companies following seasonal content calendars see 67% higher engagement rates than those posting randomly.</p>

<p>Local angle content outperforms generic HVAC advice. "How Phoenix Heat Affects Your AC System" generates more local engagement than "How Heat Affects Air Conditioners." Include local weather patterns, utility costs, and regional HVAC challenges specific to your service areas.</p>
</div>

